=== 2026-03-07 00:40 — Fix Roku video streaming (full-range 206) ===
Diagnosed and fixed Roku playback failure at ~1 minute mark.

Root cause: VideoStreamServlet's 16 MiB chunk cap on Range responses. The Roku
sends open-ended Range headers (e.g., bytes=0-) and expects the server to stream
the full file via a persistent connection with TCP flow control. The 16 MiB cap
forced the Roku into a multi-request pattern it doesn't follow — after receiving
the first 16 MiB, the Roku never requested more data and failed with "malformed
data" (-5) when the buffer was exhausted (~1 minute of video).

Iterative debugging:
1. Restored 16 MiB cap with proper 206 headers (baseline: plays ~1 min, then fails)
2. Analyzed server logs: Roku makes 6 rapid parallel requests in first 0.3s,
   all in the 0-19MiB range, some canceled (connection reset). No further
   requests ever made — Roku expects continuous streaming, not chunked fetching.
3. Removed chunk cap entirely + added proper response headers (resp.status=206,
   Content-Range, Content-Length) — this was the fix. Previous no-cap attempt
   failed because response headers were missing entirely.

Key insight: Normal HTTP servers (Apache/Nginx) serve the full requested range
and let TCP flow control handle backpressure. The artificial 16 MiB cap was a
workaround that only delayed the failure by one buffer's worth of playback.

Also fixed Jetty idle timeout (300s, up from 30s default) in previous iteration
to prevent timeout kills on long-lived streaming connections.

Files modified:
- VideoStreamServlet.kt — removed maxChunkSize cap, added proper 206 response
  headers (Content-Range, Content-Length, explicit status code)
- Main.kt — Jetty idle timeout override (from previous iteration, already committed)
- FEATURES.md — updated 9g description

Docker images deployed: 202603070029 (cap+headers), 202603070036 (no-cap+headers, final)
